Epistles styled Catliolic is said to be by James the Lord's brother. But Ι must remark that it is held by some to be spurious. Certainly not many old writers have mentioned it, as neither have they the Epistle of Jude, which is also one of the seven so-called Catholic Epistles’ (ih. ii. 23). His own practice, however, betrays no suspicion of its genuineness, as in one passage he quotes James iv. 11 as Scripture (C'omm. in Psalm. p. 648 Montf.), in another quotes J ames V. 13 as spoken by the holy Apostle (ih. p. 247). The doubt as to the canonicity of the Epistle in early times is sufficiently shown by its omission from some of the early versions and catalogues of Sacred Books. Thus it is omitted from the earliest extant catalogue, contained in what is known as the Muratorian Fragment, of which Bp. Westcott says that it may be regarded as ‘a summary of the opinion of the Western Chureh on the Canon shortly after the middle of the second century.' 1 Of the disputed books this contains two Epistles of St. John, the Apocalypse, and Jude, omitting Hebrews, dames, and Peter 1, 2.
